AUDIO_CONTENT_il it was undeniable.

The clouds were frozen.

Mid-drift.

A long, stretched formation hung above the hills like a brushstroke abandoned halfway across a canvas. Birds were suspended in the air, wings extended, as though time itself had forgotten how to move them.

One of them—just above the mango tree—was completely still.

Not hovering.

Not gliding.

Stopped.

Miriam staggered backward.

This was wrong. Not strange, not unusual—wrong. The kind of wrong that made your body react before your mind could understand.

She turned in a slow circle.

Everyone was looking up now.

Faces tilted toward the sky, eyes wide, mouths moving in silent questions. Panic spread not through sound, but through motion—jerky, uncertain, contagious.

An old man dropped to his knees.

A mother grabbed her child.

Someone began to run.

Miriam didn’t move.

She couldn’t.

Because in that frozen sky—

Something moved.

At first, she thought it was her imagination. A trick of the light, a desperate attempt by her mind to restore order to something that had none.

But then she saw it again.

A ripple.

Not in the clouds—but behind them.

Like something vast shifting just out of sight.

Her breath hitched.

Slowly, carefully, she took a step back.

And then another.

The ground felt unsteady beneath her feet, though it hadn’t changed. Or maybe it had, and she just couldn’t tell anymore.

The ripple came again.

Stronger this time.

The frozen birds did not react.

The clouds did not move.

Only that thing—whatever it was—shifted behind the sky, as if the sky itself were nothing more than a thin veil stretched over something enormous.

Something awake.

Miriam’s chest tightened.

For a moment, she forgot about the silence.

Forgot about the village.

Forgot about everything except the overwhelming certainty pressing down on her:

They were not alone.

And whatever had taken the sky—

Had just noticed them.